                <h1 class="nhsuk-u-margin-bottom-5">Buttons</h1>
                <p class="nhsuk-body-l nhsuk-u-margin-bottom-8">Use the button component to help users carry out an action on a page like starting an application or saving their progress.</p>

            </div>
    </div> 

    

  <div class="nhsuk-grid-row">
    <div class="nhsuk-grid-column-two-thirds">

<p>We have 3 buttons</p>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="#primary-button">Primary button</a></li>
        <li><a href="#secondary-button">Secondary button</a></li>
        <li><a href="#reverse-button">White button on solid background colour (reverse button)</a></li>
        </ul>

										
            <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-8"  id="primary-button">Primary button</h2>
                <div class="example grey-background nhsuk-u-margin-bottom-4">
                    {% from 'components/button/macro.njk' import button %}

                        {{ button({
                        "text": "Save and continue"
                        }) }}
                </div>

            <p><a href="https://nhsuk.github.io/nhsuk-frontend/components/button/index.html">Preview the button component</a></p>
            <p>You can <a href="https://github.com/nhsuk/nhsuk-frontend/tree/master/packages/components/button">get the latest button code</a> in the NHS.UK frontend library in GitHub.</p>

        <h3>When to use a primary button</h3>
            <p>Use the primary button to help users carry out an action on a page like starting an application or saving their progress.</p> 
            <p>Keep GOV.UK's <a href="https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/design/form-structure#start-with-one-thing-per-page">'Start with one thing per page' guidance</a> in mind when using buttons.</p>


            <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-8"  id="secondary-button">Secondary button</h2>
                <div class="example grey-background nhsuk-u-margin-bottom-4">
                        {% from 'components/button/macro.njk' import button %}

                        {{ button({
                        "text": "Find my location",
                        "classes": "nhsuk-button--secondary"
                        }) }}
                </div>

            <p><a href="https://nhsuk.github.io/nhsuk-frontend/components/button/secondary.html">Preview the button component</a></p>
            <p>You can <a href="https://github.com/nhsuk/nhsuk-frontend/tree/master/packages/components/button">get the latest button code</a> in the NHS.UK frontend library in GitHub.</p>
        <h3>When to use a secondary button</h3> 
            <p>Use a secondary button on pages that have multiple actions or when standard link text isn't being noticed by users.</p>
            <p>Keep GOV.UK's <a href="https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/design/form-structure#start-with-one-thing-per-page">'Start with one thing per page' guidance</a> in mind when using buttons.</p>

            <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-8"  id="reverse-button">White button on solid background colour (reverse button)</h2>
                <div class="example grey-background nhsuk-u-margin-bottom-4" style="background-color: #005eb8;">
                        {% from 'components/button/macro.njk' import button %}

                        {{ button({
                        "text": "Save and continue",
                        "classes": "nhsuk-button--reverse"
                        }) }}
                </div>

            <p><a href="https://nhsuk.github.io/nhsuk-frontend/components/button/reverse.html">Preview the button component</a></p>
            <p>You can <a href="https://github.com/nhsuk/nhsuk-frontend/tree/master/packages/components/button">get the latest button code</a> in the NHS.UK frontend library in GitHub.</p>

        <h3>When to use a white button on solid background colour button</h3>
            <p>White buttons on solid background colour are good on components such as interuption cards (see the intruption card being used on <a href="https://your-data-matters.service.nhs.uk/">Find out why your NHS data matters</a>), where link text, primary and secondary buttons would be lost.   </p>


            <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-8" id="how-to-use-care-cards">How to use buttons</h2>

                    <p><a href="https://design-system.service.gov.uk/">GOV.UK design system</a> suggests using the button component to help users carry out an action on a page like starting an application or saving their progress.</p>
                    <p>This advice relates to starting or saving transactional journeys, not links from one flat content page to another.</p>
                    <p>Write button text in sentence case, describing the action it performs. For example ‘Save and continue’ or ‘Start now’.</p>
                    <p>Align the primary action button to the left edge of your form.</p>

                <h3>Disabled buttons</h3>
                    <p>Disabled buttons have poor contrast and can confuse some users, so avoid them if possible.</p>
                    <p>Only use disabled buttons if research shows it makes the user interface easier to understand.</p>

                    <p>We have developed disabled versions of the three buttons shown above but they're yet to be tested. You can <a href="https://github.com/nhsuk/nhsuk-frontend/tree/master/packages/components/button">get the latest disabled button code</a> in the NHS.UK frontend library in GitHub.</p>

                <h3>Accessibility</h3>
                    <p>Make sure the text used describes the action.</p>
                    <p>All three active buttons pass AAA guidelines for colour contrast. The colour contrast ratio between text and background colour is as follows:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Primary button 5.12:1</li>
                            <li>Secondary button 7.75:1</li> 
                            <li>White button on solid background colour  14.42:1</li>   

                         </ul>   

                    <p>Please note that the disabled versions of the three buttons do not meet accessibility colour contrast ratios. If your team have discovered a user need for disabled buttons, use with caution and test with users with access needs.</p>
                


             <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-8"  id="when-not-to-use-this-component">When not to use this component</h2>  
                    <p>Don't use buttons as links to non related pages or external websites.</p>    
                    <p>Try not to have multiple buttons on one page, we suggest following GOV.UK 'one thing per page' advice <a href="https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/design/form-structure">https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/design/form-structure</a></p> 
                    
                    
                        





            <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-8"  id="research">Research</h2>

                    <p>Primary buttons were tested as part of a register with a GP form. Users understood that it was a button and knew what action it performed. All participants were able to complete the set task.</p>











